<section class="copy-section mt-5">
    <h2 class="text-center mb-4">
        What is a True Copy Apostille? – A Complete Guide
    </h2>
    <div class="container">
        <p>
            A <strong>True Copy Apostille</strong> is a certification process that verifies a digital or physical copy of an original document as a <strong>True and Accurate</strong> representation of the original. This process is widely used for legal, educational, business, and immigration purposes when an original document cannot be directly apostilled.
        </p>
        <p>
            Our online True Copy Apostille service simplifies the authentication process, allowing you to get an apostille from a certified digital copy. We affix a <strong>custodial certificate</strong>, which includes a notarized statement certifying that the document provided by you is a valid copy of the original in your possession. This notarized statement, along with your document copy, is then officially apostilled.
        </p>
        <h3 class="mt-4">How Does the True Copy Apostille Process Work?</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Step 1:</strong> You submit a high-quality scanned copy of your original document.</li>
            <li><strong>Step 2:</strong> We issue a <strong>custodial certificate</strong> that certifies your document as a true copy.</li>
            <li><strong>Step 3:</strong> Our certified notary notarizes the custodial certificate.</li>
            <li><strong>Step 4:</strong> The notarized custodial certificate, along with your document, is submitted for Apostille.</li>
            <li><strong>Step 5:</strong> Once the Apostille is obtained, we securely deliver your certified document to you.</li>
        </ul>
        <h3 class="mt-4">Where Can a True Copy Apostille Be Used?</h3>
        <p class="text-start">
            A True Copy Apostille is commonly required for various purposes, such as:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>Legal document authentication (e.g., contracts, power of attorney)</li>
            <li>Visa and immigration applications</li>
            <li>Business registration and corporate filings</li>
            <li>Educational document validation (e.g., diplomas, transcripts)</li>
            <li>Financial and banking-related certifications</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            While this method is widely accepted in most cases, its acceptance depends on the authority or country where you intend to use the document. Some government institutions may require an apostille directly on the original document rather than a certified copy.
        </p>
        <h3 class="mt-4">Is a True Copy Apostille Right for You?</h3>
        <p>
            Before requesting a True Copy Apostille, it’s important to verify with the receiving authority whether they accept apostilled copies. While many international agencies recognize this method, requirements vary by country and institution.
        </p>
        <p>
            If you need assistance with your Apostille process or have questions about document eligibility, our team is here to help. Contact us today to start your authentication process hassle-free!
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

